          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily use across Mac, iPhone, iPad, and Apple Watch</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> <strong>Things 3</strong> is the best Apple-only task manager for personal productivity in 2026. The design is the best of any task app we have used, the GTD workflow is native and complete, and Things Cloud sync is fast and reliable across Mac, iPhone, iPad, and Apple Watch. The one-time purchase model — $49.99 for Mac, $19.99 for iPad, $9.99 for iPhone — saves years of subscription fees. The lack of Windows, Android, collaboration, and kanban features limits its appeal to solo Apple users, but for that audience it is unmatched.
      </div>

      <p>Things 3, by German developer Cultured Code, has been a fixture of Apple-only productivity since its 2017 launch and won an Apple Design Award for its craft. We bought the Mac and iOS versions at retail and put them through 60 days of daily use, including GTD-style weekly reviews, project planning, recurring tasks, and cross-device sync, to see whether the one-time purchase model still holds up against the subscription-heavy task manager market of 2026.</p>

      <p>This review focuses on Things 3 specifically. For cross-platform alternatives with subscriptions and team features, see our <a href="/reviews/todoist-vs-ticktick/">Todoist vs TickTick</a> comparison. For a team-focused task manager for software projects, see our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this app is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Design: The Best Task App Interface We Have Used</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of Things 3 is its design. The Mac app uses a three-pane layout — sidebar with Areas and Projects, middle column with task lists, right column with task details — that feels like a native Apple app rather than a ported web app. The typography is sharp and consistent, animations are smooth without being distracting, and the color palette is restrained. After 60 days of daily use, we still found the interface a pleasure to work in, which is not something we say about most task managers.</p>

      <p>The iOS and iPadOS apps follow the same design language, with a two-pane layout on iPad (sidebar plus task list) and a single-pane layout on iPhone. The Apple Watch app is limited to viewing and checking off Today tasks, but it works reliably for quick glances. Cross-platform consistency is one of the strongest arguments for Things 3 — every platform feels native, not ported.</p>

      <p>The Magic Plus gesture on iPad and iPhone is a small but delightful feature. Drag down and to the right with one finger from any list, and a new task appears exactly where you dropped it, pre-filled with the current date and ready for typing. It removes the friction of menu navigation and makes capturing tasks on iPad genuinely fast. The Mac equivalent is a global keyboard shortcut (Ctrl+Space) that opens a quick-entry panel from anywhere, even when the app is not focused.</p>

      <h3>GTD Workflow: Native, Not Bolted On</h3>
      <p>Things 3 supports the Getting Things Done methodology natively, not as a plugin. The Inbox captures quick entries that you process later. Areas group projects by life context (Work, Personal, Family). Projects hold multi-step work with headings, checklists, and nested to-dos. The Today view surfaces what to do today; the Upcoming view shows dated tasks; the Anytime view shows everything active; the Someday bucket holds ideas without deadlines. The Logbook keeps completed work for weekly review.</p>

      <p>The only GTD gap is the lack of native contexts (e.g., @computer, @phone). Most users replace contexts with tags, which Things 3 supports — but tags are flat, not hierarchical, and they do not integrate with the Today view the way contexts would in a strict GTD app. For most personal productivity workflows, this is a non-issue. For strict GTD practitioners who rely on contexts, OmniFocus is the more complete (and more expensive) alternative.</p>

      <p>Recurring tasks work reliably. We set up daily, weekly, and monthly recurring tasks with natural language input ("every Friday", "first Monday of the month", "every 2 weeks starting tomorrow") and they all triggered correctly across 60 days of testing. Tasks can repeat based on completion date or scheduled date, which is a subtle but powerful option for habit-tracking workflows.</p>

      <h3>Things Cloud Sync: Fast and Encrypted</h3>
      <p>Things Cloud sync is included free with each platform purchase, with no separate subscription. In our 60 days of testing across two Macs, an iPhone, an iPad, and an Apple Watch, sync completed in 1 to 3 seconds over Wi-Fi and 5 to 10 seconds over cellular. We never experienced data loss, sync conflicts, or duplicated tasks. Cultured Code uses end-to-end encryption for sync, so your task data is not readable on their servers — a meaningful privacy advantage over cloud-only task managers.</p>

      <p>The initial setup is a single sign-in with a Things Cloud account on each device. After that, sync is automatic and transparent. There is no manual sync button and no sync status indicator beyond a brief spinner when changes arrive. For users who only use Things 3 on one device, Things Cloud can be skipped entirely — the app works fully offline with local storage. Things Cloud is only required for cross-device sync.</p>

      <p>The one limitation is that Things Cloud syncs only between your own devices. There is no shared project or collaboration feature — you cannot invite another user to a project, assign tasks, or comment. If you need any form of collaboration, Things 3 is the wrong app. This is a deliberate design choice by Cultured Code, which has positioned Things 3 as a personal productivity tool, not a team tool.</p>

      <h3>One-Time Purchase: The Anti-Subscription Argument</h3>
      <p>The pricing model is the strongest argument for Things 3 in 2026. The Mac version is $49.99, the iPad version is $19.99, and the iPhone version is $9.99 — paid once, owned forever, with no recurring fees. Things Cloud sync is included free. Over three years, the total cost of all three platforms ($79.97) is less than a single year of Todoist Pro ($48) plus two years — and you own the app, not a rental.</p>

      <p>Cultured Code has shipped free updates to Things 3 for over seven years since the 2017 launch, including compatibility updates for every macOS and iOS release. The app still receives bug fixes and minor feature additions. A future Things 4 would likely be a new paid upgrade, but Cultured Code has not announced one, and Things 3 remains fully supported and current in 2026.</p>

      <p>The downside is the lack of a free tier and no trial. You pay per platform before you can test the full app — there is no 14-day trial and no freemium mode. The Mac App Store does offer refunds within 14 days in some regions, but you are otherwise committing $49.99 sight-unseen. For most Apple users who have already heard of Things 3, this is an acceptable risk; for first-time buyers, it is a real friction point.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>Things 3 competes against Todoist, TickTick, OmniFocus, Apple Reminders, and Notion. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>App</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Platforms</th>
            <th>Collaboration</th>
            <th>Design</th>
            <th>Kanban</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Things 3</strong></td>
            <td>$49.99 (once)</td>
            <td>Apple only</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Best</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Todoist Pro</td>
            <td>$4/month</td>
            <td>All</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>Yes (board)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>TickTick</td>
            <td>$3/month</td>
            <td>All</td>
            <td>Limited</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>OmniFocus 3</td>
            <td>$99.99 (once)</td>
            <td>Apple only</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Apple Reminders</td>
            <td>Free</td>
            <td>Apple only</td>
            <td>Yes (shared)</td>
            <td>Good</td>
            <td>No</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Todoist</strong> is the most popular cross-platform alternative. It costs $4/month for Pro, supports every platform including web, has natural language input on par with Things 3, and includes team collaboration, kanban boards, and integrations. The trade-off is a subscription model and a less polished design. Choose Things 3 if you are Apple-only and want to own your app; choose Todoist if you need cross-platform access, collaboration, or kanban. See our <a href="/reviews/todoist-vs-ticktick/">Todoist vs TickTick</a> comparison for the deeper breakdown.</p>

      <p><strong>TickTick</strong> is the value subscription alternative at $3/month. It matches Todoist on features and adds a built-in Pomodoro timer and habit tracker. The design is good but not at Things 3's level. For users who want a timer and habit tracking built in, TickTick is the more complete app for less money.</p>

      <p><strong>OmniFocus 3</strong> is the strict-GTD Apple-only alternative at $99.99. It supports native contexts, custom perspectives, and more complex workflows than Things 3 — at the cost of a steeper learning curve and a higher price. Choose OmniFocus if you are a strict GTD practitioner who needs contexts and perspectives; choose Things 3 if you want a simpler, more beautiful app.</p>

      <p><strong>Apple Reminders</strong> is the free Apple-only alternative. It is pre-installed on every iPhone, iPad, and Mac, supports shared lists, and has natural language input. The trade-off is no areas, no headings, no project hierarchy, and a less powerful editor. For casual task management, Reminders is enough; for project work, Things 3 is a meaningful upgrade.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy Things 3 for Mac at full price if you are an Apple-only user who wants the best-designed task manager and prefers owning your app over renting it. The $49.99 one-time purchase saves years of subscription fees compared to Todoist or TickTick, and the design and GTD workflow are unmatched on Apple platforms.</p>

      <p>Buy the iPad version ($19.99) if you use an iPad regularly. The Magic Plus gesture and two-pane layout make the iPad version the best mobile task experience we have used, and it justifies the price for serious iPad users. The iPhone version ($9.99) is worth it for the quick-entry widget and Apple Watch glance alone.</p>

      <p>Skip Things 3 and use Todoist if you need Windows, Android, or web access, or if you need team collaboration, kanban boards, or integrations. Todoist Pro at $4/month is the better choice for cross-platform and team users. See our <a href="/reviews/todoist-vs-ticktick/">Todoist vs TickTick</a> comparison for the deeper breakdown.</p>

      <p>Use Apple Reminders instead if you only need casual task management and want to spend $0. Reminders is free, supports shared lists, and is good enough for simple to-do lists. Things 3 is a meaningful upgrade only if you manage projects with headings, areas, and recurring tasks.</p>

      <p>Consider OmniFocus 3 if you are a strict GTD practitioner who needs native contexts and custom perspectives. OmniFocus is $99.99 — twice the price of Things 3 — and has a steeper learning curve, but it is the more complete GTD tool. For most personal productivity users, Things 3 is the better balance of power and simplicity. Pair Things 3 with a <a href="/reviews/best-password-managers-2026/">password manager</a> and a <a href="/reviews/best-cloud-storage-2026/">cloud storage service</a> for a complete personal productivity stack.</p>

